# Project Evolution

## Overview

What started as a small Python script built out of frustration during a difficult job search slowly evolved into a much larger technical and personal learning experience.

The original goal was extremely simple: automate the most repetitive and emotionally exhausting part of looking for a job — searching through hundreds of job posts manually every day.

Over time, the project evolved into:

- a large-scale exploration of ethical scraping patterns,
- infrastructure limitations,
- observability and debugging,
- search optimization,
- human behavior modeling,
- user friction reduction,
- and eventually a complete pivot away from scraping as the core product idea.

The project ultimately reached a point where the focus stopped being "how to scrape better" and became:

> "How can a system better understand human intent during the job search process?"

That question became the foundation for the next stage of development.

---

## Initial Idea

The initial idea was born from frustration.

Like many people in the tech industry, especially during difficult hiring periods, I spent a large amount of time refreshing LinkedIn, filtering jobs manually, opening posts, closing posts, changing filters, and repeating the same process every day.

Ironically, the most exhausting part of applying for jobs was not preparing for interviews or improving skills.

It was simply searching.

At the time, I realized that most of my search behavior was repetitive:

- I used the same keywords every day.
- I applied the same filters repeatedly.
- I checked the same pages constantly.
- I refreshed listings manually hoping to be early enough.

The project started as a simple attempt to automate that repetitive behavior.

Not to build a platform.  
Not to build a company.  
Not to monetize anything.

Just to reduce mental exhaustion.

---

## First Automation Workflow

The very first version of the project was extremely small.

It was a simple Python script of roughly 20 lines.

At the time, my understanding of LinkedIn's search system was very superficial. I noticed that many search filters could be manipulated directly through the URL structure itself, so instead of thinking deeply about scraping architecture or backend systems, I focused on replicating my own manual behavior.

The script simply:

1. Opened LinkedIn job search pages.
2. Used predefined keyword filters.
3. Scanned titles.
4. Compared results against a list of around 15 keywords.
5. Sent matching offers back as results.

The filtering logic itself was primitive but surprisingly effective.

If a job title matched at least two predefined keywords, the system considered it relevant enough.

At this stage, the goal was not precision.  
The goal was speed.

The idea was simple:

> "If I am already doing this manually every day, why not automate it and expand the search scope at the same time?"

This was also the first moment where I realized automation could directly improve my response time during hiring processes.

---

## Transition to Telegram

Once the script successfully worked for the first time, a new problem immediately appeared.

Receiving results by email was too slow.

At the time, one of my biggest frustrations with LinkedIn was notification delay. Many good job opportunities disappeared quickly or reached hundreds of applicants within minutes.

My first reaction was honestly chaotic.

I briefly considered:

- email integrations,
- Salesforce API bridges,
- WhatsApp notifications,
- and several unnecessarily complex ideas driven mostly by frustration.

The WhatsApp approach was quickly discarded.

Not only because the API was paid and restrictive, but because it introduced unnecessary complexity into what was still just a small personal automation script.

Telegram became the obvious solution.

Not because I initially understood its ecosystem, open-source philosophy, or bot infrastructure.

But because it solved the only problem I cared about at that moment:

> instant delivery.

Telegram was the first major technological shift in the project.

It introduced:

- API integrations,
- messaging systems,
- user interaction flows,
- and the first real feeling that the project was becoming something larger than a simple script.

This was also the first moment where the project started feeling personally meaningful.

---

## Infrastructure Exploration

As soon as the automation became functional, another major limitation appeared.

The script still depended on a computer staying permanently active.

At the time, I did not own a working personal computer. I depended on borrowing my brother's laptop whenever he had free time available.

That immediately made the project unreliable.

The system could not truly be "automatic" if:

- the machine was unavailable,
- the laptop had to remain turned on constantly,
- or someone else needed to sacrifice resources and time for the project to continue running.

This forced me into cloud infrastructure much earlier than expected.

Initially, I approached cloud systems with almost no infrastructure knowledge.

My first attempt was Google Cloud.

I tried activating the free trial multiple times, failed repeatedly, became frustrated, and then started researching alternatives more seriously.

That process eventually led me to Oracle Cloud Infrastructure.

OCI was not beginner-friendly.

At the time, I did not fully understand:

- regions,
- instances,
- processors,
- memory allocation,
- long-term account limitations,
- or cloud provisioning.

I relied heavily on AI guidance simply to get started.

Using step-by-step assistance, I created my first instance without fully understanding what I was configuring:

- AMD processor,
- 1 GB RAM,
- minimal storage,
- Ubuntu image,
- Python environment,
- dependencies and libraries.

But despite all the ignorance surrounding the setup process, it worked.

The bot successfully ran remotely.

That moment was extremely important.

It was the first time the project stopped feeling like a local script and started feeling like an actual deployable system.

## Android Development Environment

Losing access to a proper computer completely changed the direction of the project.

At that point, development depended on borrowing my brother’s laptop whenever he had free time. The problem was that he was finishing his thesis and final university project, so free time barely existed. What started as a small automation script suddenly became something I genuinely cared about, and the lack of hardware became a real limitation.

The more I learned about cloud infrastructure, deployment environments, and automation, the more motivated I became. For the first time, I was not building a generic portfolio project copied from a tutorial or designed to “look good” on a resume. This was solving a real problem I was personally experiencing.

Instead of accepting hardware limitations as a blocker, I started looking for alternatives.

I remembered an old Android phone stored in a drawer:

- 6GB RAM
- 128GB storage
- Completely unused

At first the idea sounded ridiculous, but after researching modern Android development environments, I realized phones had become surprisingly powerful. Even though it was not a high-end device, it still offered significantly more resources than the free Oracle instance I had initially deployed.

That was the moment I stopped treating infrastructure as something external and started treating it as part of the engineering challenge itself.

I formatted the device and turned it into a dedicated development environment:

- Installed Termux
- Installed Acode
- Rebuilt the entire workflow around mobile development
- Started working directly from the phone

The experience was chaotic but transformative.

Android development environments introduce a completely different category of problems:

- package incompatibilities
- broken dependencies
- unstable Linux behavior under Android
- restricted filesystem permissions
- missing native libraries
- inconsistent support for Python tooling

At first, almost every development session became a battle against the environment itself.

But strangely, that became part of the motivation.

Instead of seeing the limitations as frustrating, I started seeing them as engineering constraints that forced creativity and adaptability. Every problem solved taught me something new about Linux environments, dependency management, Python packaging, infrastructure isolation, and deployment strategies.

The Android setup eventually became more than just a temporary workaround.

It became:

- my development machine
- my testing environment
- my deployment environment
- my experimentation sandbox

And more importantly, it removed the dependency on external conditions.

I no longer had to wait for access to somebody else’s computer to keep building.

