## Scaling Challenges

As the project evolved, every solved problem revealed a new limitation behind it.

The original Oracle Cloud instance had been enough for a simple proof of concept, but once the bot started growing in complexity and usage patterns became more demanding, the infrastructure limitations became impossible to ignore.

The instance only had:

- 1GB RAM
- limited CPU resources
- minimal storage
- almost no room for experimentation

For me and a couple of friends, it was technically functional, but the project had already outgrown its original purpose.

At the same time, the Android environment solved some problems while creating entirely new ones.

I now had more local resources than the cloud instance itself, but development became increasingly difficult because of:

- compatibility issues
- broken packages
- Linux emulation limitations
- Python dependency conflicts
- Android restrictions
- unstable development workflows

The deeper I went into infrastructure and automation, the more time I spent solving environment problems instead of improving the product itself.

At the same time, my mental state started deteriorating without me noticing it.

Originally, the project progressed slowly because development time depended on borrowing a laptop. Once the Android setup removed that limitation, I suddenly had unrestricted access to the project at all times.

That changed everything.

I started spending:

- 10 hours a day
- sometimes 12+
- sleeping poorly
- constantly thinking about optimizations
- constantly testing new ideas

The project evolved faster than my ability to organize it.

Code grew aggressively.

Ideas multiplied faster than implementation quality.

What started as a small script slowly transformed into a massive monolithic system full of:

- experimental logic
- unfinished refactors
- temporary patches
- duplicated flows
- loose threads
- undocumented behavior
- partially implemented features

At one point the codebase reached nearly 3000 lines inside a single functional structure.

And despite being functional, internally it was becoming extremely fragile.

Instead of properly organizing systems before expanding them, I became obsessed with refining scraping behavior itself.

The challenge stopped being:

> “Can I automate job searching?”

And became:

> “Can I make scraping behavior indistinguishable from human behavior?”

That shift pushed me into an entirely different category of research.

I started studying:

- LinkedIn behavior patterns
- anti-bot detection systems
- request pacing
- timing randomness
- interaction intervals
- scraping aggressiveness
- regional limitations
- job posting patterns
- user interaction simulation
- HTML structure hierarchy
- market activity cycles

I experimented with concepts that never even reached production:

- IP randomization ideas
- behavioral timing systems
- randomized delays
- jitter systems
- adaptive scan intervals
- non-linear interaction patterns

Eventually I reached a point where the scraping behavior became highly optimized and extremely difficult to distinguish from normal user behavior.

The system dynamically adjusted:

- scan frequency
- pauses
- interruptions
- request pacing
- interaction timing

All while maximizing vacancy coverage for the user without creating aggressive patterns against LinkedIn.

At the same time, search logic itself was evolving independently.

The original scoring model was extremely simple:

- minimum keyword matches
- basic title filtering
- hard inclusion logic

But the more I observed how people actually searched for jobs, the more I realized users themselves were often the biggest bottleneck in search quality.

That realization changed the direction of the research completely.

Instead of trying to aggressively improve extraction, I started trying to improve interpretation.

The focus shifted toward:

- reducing false positives
- improving result quality
- making searches feel personalized
- balancing user control with automation
- minimizing friction
- refining intent interpretation

This led to increasingly complex experimentation:

- exclusion keywords
- scoring systems
- weighted logic
- conditional filtering
- user-controlled refinement
- dynamic search structures

And all of it existed inside an increasingly unstable monolithic codebase.

