## Observability and Debugging

At the beginning, debugging was simple.

Problems were obvious:

- loops repeating incorrectly
- broken logic chains
- disconnected conditions
- functions failing visibly

The solution mindset was reactive:

> “Fix what is broken and continue.”

But because the project evolved without a long-term architectural plan, the codebase slowly became dominated by temporary fixes instead of structured systems.

The project accumulated:

- patches over patches
- incomplete comments
- inconsistent logic
- duplicated behaviors
- disconnected flows
- debugging shortcuts

Testing also became chaotic.

Instead of validating systems holistically, I kept following an isolated cycle:

1. test one thing
2. find a problem
3. patch it
4. continue
5. accidentally break something else
6. repeat

The larger the project became, the harder it became to understand whether new bugs were caused by:

- old logic
- recent patches
- hidden dependencies
- unintended side effects

At the same time, the project started emotionally expanding beyond the code itself.

I had already shown the bot to:

- my parents
- my brother
- close friends

And their reactions affected me more than expected.

For the first time, I was not only thinking technically.

I started thinking about:

- usability
- accessibility
- user frustration
- search fatigue
- interaction flow
- emotional experience

Ironically, while trying to solve those higher-level problems, I was neglecting the technical foundation underneath everything.

Technical debt accumulated rapidly.

