## Search Pattern Optimization

Eventually, scraping behavior and search behavior stopped feeling like the same problem.

That distinction became one of the most important turning points of the entire project.

At first, I believed LinkedIn restricted important filters unless the user was authenticated with a valid session token.

Because of that assumption, I initially experimented with:

- authenticated requests
- personal token usage
- session-based filtering
- API alternatives

None of those approaches were scalable or reasonable.

The more I studied LinkedIn’s actual HTML structure and filtering hierarchy, the more I realized my original assumptions were wrong.

The platform itself was not heavily restricting filters based on authentication.

Most filtering behavior came from relatively simple hierarchical logic structures.

That realization changed everything.

Instead of trying to optimize scraping through authentication tricks or more aggressive extraction methods, I decided to redesign the entire search philosophy.

The user would now become responsible for refining intent.

The bot would become responsible for extraction efficiency and interpretation.

That distinction fundamentally changed the system.

Instead of asking users for isolated keywords, I started asking them to think like real job seekers:

- desired job titles
- realistic searches
- human phrasing
- actual search intent

This allowed the system to behave much more naturally.

Using LinkedIn’s own search hierarchy, the bot could:

1. perform human-like searches
2. refine results dynamically
3. reduce unnecessary scans
4. minimize false positives
5. decrease scraping aggressiveness

At the same time, users gained more control over how searches behaved.

I experimented with:

- advanced searches
- simplified searches
- flexible scoring
- weighted averages
- exclusion systems
- customizable thresholds

Eventually I reached an important conclusion:

Traditional keyword matching was too restrictive.

The real problem was not extraction.

The real problem was understanding intent.

That realization became the foundation for everything that came after.

The focus slowly shifted away from scraping itself and toward creating systems capable of reducing the gap between:

- what users actually want
- and how users explain what they want

---

## Modularization

Modularization should have happened much earlier.

But at the time, the project evolved too quickly for me to recognize how dangerous the architecture had become.

The system was technically functional, but internally it was collapsing under its own complexity.

The monolithic structure contained:

- nearly 3000 lines of code
- undocumented logic
- scattered comments
- temporary fixes
- experimental systems
- duplicated flows
- mixed responsibilities

And most importantly:

Everything was organized around technologies instead of responsibilities.

The project was separated by:

- scraping logic
- Telegram interactions
- infrastructure experiments
- filtering systems

But not by actual functional architecture.

Eventually, the pressure became impossible to ignore.

At that point modularization stopped being a “good practice” idea and became a survival necessity.

Ironically, the process of modularizing the project ended up reorganizing my own thinking as well.

Once I started separating responsibilities clearly, I realized something extremely important:

The project no longer needed to depend entirely on scraping behavior.

I started exploring:

- SQLite databases
- local persistence
- historical vacancy tracking
- cached interpretation systems
- user-driven refinement

And eventually I discovered Pydantic V2.

That became another major technical turning point.

Unfortunately, Android environments introduced severe compatibility limitations with modern Python tooling.

To properly support newer dependency structures, I had to isolate the development environment completely.

That led to another infrastructure transition:

- Debian inside Termux
- isolated Linux environment
- separated development layers
- proper dependency control

After weeks of instability, patches, failures, and experimentation, I finally reached something that felt like a clean starting point again.

For the first time in a long time, I had:

- a functional isolated environment
- a clearer architectural vision
- a cleaner separation of responsibilities
- and a realistic path forward

---

## Pivot Toward Search-Oriented Systems

Once the architecture started becoming clearer, the biggest realization finally appeared:

I no longer needed to optimize scraping itself.

I had already gone beyond that.

The real value was never extraction.

The real value was interpretation.

The deeper I researched user behavior, job searching frustration, and filtering systems, the more obvious it became that the real problem was not lack of information.

The real problem was the gap between:

- human intention
- and machine interpretation

At that point the project fundamentally changed direction.

The goal was no longer:

> “Build a better scraper.”

The goal became:

> “Build a better search experience.”

That did not mean abandoning the entire scraping research process.

On the contrary.

Everything learned during scraping optimization became foundational knowledge for the next phase.

The scraping research became:

- the technical foundation
- the experimentation layer
- the behavioral analysis phase
- the infrastructure learning process

But the future vision became something much larger:

- search-oriented systems
- intent interpretation
- personalized filtering
- user-centered discovery
- adaptive recommendation systems

The project stopped being about extraction engines.

And started becoming about helping people communicate what they are actually looking for.
